<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="458">
Etymology L 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33875" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole minutula Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole minutula Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="458" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutula">minutula</taxonomicName>
, very small.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="458">diagnosis A very small, yellow species, found in the myrmecophyte Maieta, distinguished in the major by the relatively high, subangulate humerus seen in dorsal-oblique view, the extrusion of the humeral angles slightly beyond the lower part of the pronotum beneath when seen from above, and the parallel longitudinal carinulae covering the anterior half of the head capsule; and in both castes by the mostly smooth and shiny body surface.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="458">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181913" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole nitidicollis Emery" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole nitidicollis Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="458" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidicollis">nitidicollis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34045" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole tenerescens Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole tenerescens Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="458" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenerescens">tenerescens</taxonomicName>
but distinguished by its flatter promesonotal profile, much shallower occiput in full-face view, and absence of transverse carinulae on the anterior pronotal dorsum. See also the less similar 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33595" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole arhuaca Forel" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole arhuaca Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="458" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arhuaca">arhuaca</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181873" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole flavifrons Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole flavifrons Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="458" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavifrons">flavifrons</taxonomicName>
, and other species listed as close to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33595" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole arhuaca Forel" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole arhuaca Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="458" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arhuaca">arhuaca</taxonomicName>
; and compare the queen to the small, possibly parasitic 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33867" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole microgyna Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole microgyna Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="458" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="microgyna">microgyna</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="458">Measurements (mm) Lectotype major: HW 0.76, HL 0.86, SL 0.42, EL 0.14, PW 0.40.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="458">Paralectotype minor: HW 0.44, HL 0.50, SL 0.38, EL 0.06, PW 0.26.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="458">Color Major: body concolorous yellow; gaster, antennae, and legs a shade lighter.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="458">Minor: concolorous yellow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="458">Range Widespread from Panama and the Guianas to Amazonian Brazil, Peru, and Ecuador.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="458">
Biology Colonies were found at Belem by Joseph Bequaert and near Manaus by myself in the swollen leaf bases of the melastome understory shrub Maieta guianensis. The species was abundant where I collected it from the swollen leaf bases of Maieta guianensis (Wilson 1984b). I was able to keep colonies alive and growing in artificial nests away from the melastomes. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33875" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole minutula Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole minutula Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="458" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutula">P. minutula</taxonomicName>
may be the host of another species, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33867" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole microgyna Wheeler" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole microgyna Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="458" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="microgyna">P. microgyna</taxonomicName>
, but the status of this form is problematic (Wilson 1984b). Winged queens have been found in nests from July to September.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
